  "prompt": "This program should return a random number from a die roll. It keeps telling me that the 'return' is outside the function. What is wrong with it?",
  "response": "It sounds like there may be an indentation issue in your code. In Python, indentation is crucial for defining the scope and structure of your code blocks. If a return statement is outside of the function, it won't work as intended.\n\nHere is an example of a simple program that returns a random number from a die roll:\n\n```python\nimport random\n\ndef roll_die():\n    return random.randint(1, 6)\n\n# Calling the function\nprint(roll_die())\n```\n\nIn this example:\n1. The `roll_die` function is defined correctly with proper indentation.\n2. The `return` statement is inside the function, returning a random integer between 1 and 6.\n3. The `print(roll_die())` line is outside the function and calls the function to print the result.\n\nMake sure that your `return` statement is inside the function and properly indented:\n\n```python\nimport random\n\ndef roll_die():\n    # Properly indented return statement\n    return random.randint(1, 6)\n\n# Calling the function\nprint(roll_die())\n```\n\nCheck your code to ensure that the `return` statement is indented properly within the function definition. If you provide the exact code you're using, I can give more specific advice.",
